README.md
     9â†’# Mitt
    11â†’> Tiny 200b functional event emitter / pubsub.
    12â†’
    13â†’-   **Microscopic:** weighs less than 200 bytes gzipped
    14â†’-   **Useful:** a wildcard `"*"` event type listens to all events
    15â†’-   **Familiar:** same names & ideas as [Node's EventEmitter](https://nodejs.org/api/events.html#events_class_eventemitter)
    16â†’-   **Functional:** methods don't rely on `this`
    17â†’-   **Great Name:** somehow [mitt](https://npm.im/mitt) wasn't taken
    18â†’
    19â†’Mitt was made for the browser, but works in any JavaScript runtime. It has no dependencies and supports IE9+.
    20â†’
    21â†’## Table of Contents
    23â†’-   [Install](#install)
    24â†’-   [Usage](#usage)
    25â†’-   [Examples & Demos](#examples--demos)
    26â†’-   [API](#api)
    27â†’-   [Contribute](#contribute)
    28â†’-   [License](#license)
    29â†’
    30â†’## Install
    32â†’This project uses [node](http://nodejs.org) and [npm](https://npmjs.com). Go check them out if you don't have them locally installed.
    33â†’
    34â†’```sh
    35â†’$ npm install --save mitt
    36â†’```
    37â†’
    38â†’Then with a module bundler like [rollup](http://rollupjs.org/) or [webpack](https://webpack.js.org/), use as you would anything else:
    39â†’
    40â†’```javascript
    41â†’// using ES6 modules
    42â†’import mitt from 'mitt'
    43â†’
    44â†’// using CommonJS modules
    45â†’var mitt = require('mitt')
    46â†’```
    47â†’
    48â†’The [UMD](https://github.com/umdjs/umd) build is also available on [unpkg](https://unpkg.com):
    49â†’
    50â†’```html
    51â†’<script src="https://unpkg.com/mitt/dist/mitt.umd.js"></script>
    52â†’```
    53â†’
    54â†’You can find the library on `window.mitt`.
    55â†’
    56â†’## Usage
    58â†’```js
    59â†’import mitt from 'mitt'
    60â†’
    61â†’const emitter = mitt()
    62â†’
    63â†’// listen to an event
    64â†’emitter.on('foo', e => console.log('foo', e) )
    65â†’
    66â†’// listen to all events
    67â†’emitter.on('*', (type, e) => console.log(type, e) )
    68â†’
    69â†’// fire an event
    70â†’emitter.emit('foo', { a: 'b' })
    71â†’
    72â†’// clearing all events
    73â†’emitter.all.clear()
    74â†’
    75â†’// working with handler references:
    76â†’function onFoo() {}
    77â†’emitter.on('foo', onFoo)   // listen
    78â†’emitter.off('foo', onFoo)  // unlisten
    79â†’```
    80â†’
    81â†’### Typescript
    83â†’Set `"strict": true` in your tsconfig.json to get improved type inference for `mitt` instance methods.
    84â†’
    85â†’```ts
    86â†’import mitt from 'mitt';
    87â†’
    88â†’type Events = {
    89â†’  foo: string;
    90â†’  bar?: number;
    91â†’};
    92â†’
    93â†’const emitter = mitt<Events>(); // inferred as Emitter<Events>
    94â†’
    95â†’emitter.on('foo', (e) => {}); // 'e' has inferred type 'string'
    96â†’
    97â†’emitter.emit('foo', 42); // Error: Argument of type 'number' is not assignable to parameter of type 'string'. (2345)
    98â†’```
    99â†’
   100â†’Alternatively, you can use the provided `Emitter` type:
   101â†’
   102â†’```ts
   103â†’import mitt, { Emitter } from 'mitt';
   104â†’
   105â†’type Events = {
   106â†’  foo: string;
   107â†’  bar?: number;
   108â†’};
   109â†’
   110â†’const emitter: Emitter<Events> = mitt<Events>();
   111â†’```
   112â†’
   113â†’## Examples & Demos
   123â†’## API
   127â†’#### Table of Contents
   129â†’-   [mitt](#mitt)
   130â†’-   [all](#all)
